Mei's Stage
London — The daunting task facing Britain's newly appointed Prime Minister Theresa May is to carry out the demand of British — or more precisely, of voters in England and Wales — to "leave the European Union" and manage the far-reaching consequences that this entails.
The challenge she faces surpasses that of any previous prime minister in recent years.
But she may have the capability to complete this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has demonstrated courage in a series of crises, all the tools needed to complete the task are in May's hands.
She is intelligent and tenacious, with no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not bound by any ideology, is very skilled at maintaining control, and operates within self-defined boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues at hand.
May achieved victory in most of the battles she participated in and showed no mercy to those who had used underhanded tactics against her.
But she has few enemies within her party and is popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — she needs to make full use of it to lead Britain's Brexit process.
The Brexit process has already begun, there is no doubt about that.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot go back.
She has repeatedly stated that "Brexit is Brexit," and her ministers all agree with her view.
But May has not yet provided an exact definition of Brexit for Britain.
This task is extremely difficult to complete.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare your food.
You find it very hard to know clearly what you will actually end up eating.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" — eggs, bacon, pork sausages, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes — with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you may feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some people may focus primarily on preventing EU labor from entering Britain.
Some may be more concerned about securing access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, Britain cannot order every dish on the menu.
The reality often overlooked by Brexit supporters is that the EU will not give Britain benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win favor or punish Britain for rejecting the EU (sometimes such inflammatory rhetoric dominates, such as the statement by the newly appointed British Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson that "Hitler-style imperialism").
In contrast, we Britons often forget that everyone—including the EU and all its member states—has their own political or commercial interests that they have sworn to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine what Britain's objectives should be after the difficult negotiations on the relationship with the EU (and in the trade field, with the rest of the world) begin on a realistic basis.
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six separate themes that need to be negotiated), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
By the time the negotiations are completed, my granddaughter, who is 11 years old now, may already be starting university!
We must clarify the priorities in order to prevent the negotiations from dragging on for even longer.
The objective is certainly to strike a balance between British exports and services (especially financial services) entering other European countries and restricting EU citizens from entering Britain.
The more negotiators gain in one area, the greater the concessions they need to make in other areas.
May needs to make full use of the knowledge, skills, and political capital she possesses to ensure the rationality of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find that dissatisfaction is not just from one part of the group—such a result is inevitable—but from all of them.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing May's government: narrowing the growing social divide in Britain exposed by Brexit.
Working-class workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, and they have long been distant from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called representatives of globalization—the European Union.
The metropolitan areas of England—especially London—may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have gained nothing.
Due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by the left-wing leader Jeremy Corbyn, many members of the working-class community ultimately became victims of the populist promises of the Brexit supporters.
"They claim we will reverse globalization."
"We will drive out immigrants who suppress wages and redirect hundreds of millions of pounds that were previously paid to the European Union into public services."
They promised that Brexit would allow Britain to return to a safer and more prosperous past.
Brexit supporters cannot truly deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, just as it cannot cut off immigration from the European Union.
Any such move would destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturn leads to a decline in immigration, those workers who voted for Brexit may still be disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and public services continue to face heavy pressure.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has unleashed an uncontrollable storm of populist sentiment.
Just like Donald Trump was powerless to improve the circumstances of working-class voters in the United States, Brexit cannot bring benefits to those who chose it, no matter how the situation seems.
Despite having many strengths, May may still be unable to overcome such a challenge.
